docs.abstract: Company leaders use the word “moat” a lot. That can sometimes invite regulatory scrutiny, as it did with Amazon, which was sued this week.
docs.snippet: Company leaders use the word “moat” a lot. That can sometimes invite regulatory scrutiny, as it did with Amazon, which was sued this week.
docs.lead_paragraph: Nvidia has been hailed by Wall Street for the “moat” it has built around its chips to power artificial intelligence systems. Starbucks wants to retain its moat in China.

headline.main: What C.E.O.s Mean When They Talk About ‘Moats’

docs.abstract: The S&P 500 is trading at a three-month low as surging oil prices, rising bond yields and concerns about economic growth send investors to the exits.
docs.snippet: The S&P 500 is trading at a three-month low as surging oil prices, rising bond yields and concerns about economic growth send investors to the exits.
docs.lead_paragraph: Stocks are heading for their worst month of the year as a triple whammy of soaring bond yields, rising oil prices and slowing growth trigger a widespread sell-off, even in once-loved mega-cap tech companies.

headline.main: What’s Driving the September Stock Swoon

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

docs.abstract: The chip designer will begin trading on Thursday, in the biggest listing of the year. Investors hope it will rejuvenate demand for new stock offerings.
docs.snippet: The chip designer will begin trading on Thursday, in the biggest listing of the year. Investors hope it will rejuvenate demand for new stock offerings.
docs.lead_paragraph: All eyes are on Arm Thursday as the chip designer prepares to begin trading on the Nasdaq in the biggest initial public offering of the year. The company priced its shares on Wendesday at $51 each, the top end of its range, valuing it at about $54.5 billion.

headline.main: Arm’s I.P.O. Delivers a Big Test for the Markets

docs.abstract: The effort by Senators Richard Blumenthal and Josh Hawley is the latest move by lawmakers to catch up with the rapidly evolving technology.
docs.snippet: The effort by Senators Richard Blumenthal and Josh Hawley is the latest move by lawmakers to catch up with the rapidly evolving technology.
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Richard Blumenthal, Democrat of Connecticut, and Senator Josh Hawley, Republican of Missouri, plan to announce a sweeping framework to regulate artificial intelligence, in the latest effort by Congress to catch up with the technology.

headline.main: 2 Senators Propose Bipartisan Framework for A.I. Laws
headline.print_headline: 2 Senators Propose Bipartisan Framework for Laws Regulating Artificial Intelligence
